## Disabled Metrics

We believe in transparency. Not all metrics can be calculated reliably using single-camera video. If a metric cannot be measured with robust mathematical certainty, we disable it rather than outputting false data to the athlete.

### Stride Length
**What it was supposed to measure:** The physical distance (in inches) from the pitching rubber to the lead foot at foot strike. Standard benchmarks prefer a stride length that is 80-90% of the pitcher's total body height.
**Why it is disabled:** 
- **Digital Panning:** Operators naturally twist and pan AWRE Cameras to follow the pitcher moving down the mound. Because the camera physically rotates, the background pixels shift continuously over the pitch delivery. 
- **Moving Origins:** Measuring the pure pixel distance between the back ankle at Set Phase and the front ankle at Foot Strike is invalidated because the camera's origin point drags along with the pitcher. 
- **Occlusion:** Tracing the pitching rubber directly also fails because pitchers regularly drag their feet over the rubber, tricking computer vision algorithms into tracking the moving shoe instead of the stationary ground.
- **Conclusion:** Without establishing a stationary 3D origin, measuring absolute Euclidean distance from single, panning cameras is not robust enough for our engine. Stride length is currently disabled and does not penalize efficiency scores.
